UNDERSTANDING THE ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE PROGRAM

CREATING YOUR OWN ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE PROGRAM

Now, your task is to code a simple assembly language program. Here’s how to do it:

Step 1: Open any text editor example NOTEPAD or TEXTPAD. A Filename or Base name with an extension name (.ASM)

 

Note: The base name for your filename must not exceed to eight (8) characters.

Parts of a Filename

  • Base name
  • Dot symbol
  • Extension name

 

Format of Filename Structure

 

                <base name> . <extension name>

 

NOTEPAD                                                                                                                            TEXTPAD

 

Step 2: Then, you can type now your program, just like using an MS Word application.

Key in the given program:


SAVING YOUR WORK

After typing the codes, save your work by clicking on Menu Bar choose File -> Save As then type the filename including extension name example: INDEX.ASM, change the SAVE AS TYPE to ALL FILES, then click SAVE.

EXITING THE EDITOR

Now it’s time to exit from the text editor and go back to DOS environment. To do this, on your Menu Bar choose File -> Exit.

HOW TO ASSEMBLE A SOURCE PROGRAM

Step1:   From the DOS prompt, type the following: TASM, followed by a space, the base name and press ENETER key.

                Note: Make sure you have the following files in your network drive

                TASM.EXE, TLINK.EXE, RTM.EXE

                Z:\>TASM LETTERA.ASM<enter>This command calls up the Turbo                                                                                                                    

ASseMbler (TASM). It creates an object module or an OBJ file (in this case, myprog.obj). If there are no errors in your program, the assembler will put on view somewhat like this on screen.

 

 

                Note: Make sure you have ERROR MESSAGE: NONE and WARNING MESSAGE: NONE.

Step2: Type on your command prompt

 

               Z:\>TLINK LETTERA –t

Step 3: To execute your program, type on your command prompt

                Z:\>LETTERA.COM

EXAMPLES OF ASSEMBLY LANGUAGE PROGRAMS

 

  • Displaying a character (uppercase ‘A’) on screen.



  • Displaying character (lowercase ‘b’) twice on screen.


  • Using control characters (0A – Line Feed and 0D – Carriage Return) in a screen display.


  • Displaying different characters (‘A’ to ‘Z’) using LOOP on the same line.

 

                   

  • Displaying string “Computer” on screen


PUSH/POP

PUSH and POP an important instruction used to store and retrieve data for LIFO stack memory. The 8086/8088 microprocessor has four forms of PUSH and POP Instructions: register, register/memory, segment register, and flags.                 

Register addressing allows the contents of any 16-bit register to be transferred to or from the stack. Register/memory addressing stores either the contents of a 16-bit register or memory location on the stack. Segment register addressing allows any segment register to be pushed onto the stack and all but the code segment register (CS) to be retrieved from the stack. The final form, flag register addressing, allows the flag or the status register to be transferred between the flag register and the stack.

PUSH

The push instruction always transfers 2 bytes of data onto the stack. Whenever data are pushed onto the stacked, the first (most significant) data byte is stored in the stack segment at the location addressed SP-1. The second (least significant) data byte is stored in the stack segment at the location address SP-2. After the data are stored by a PUSH, the SP register is decrements by a 2.

POP 

The POP instruction performs the inverse operation of a PUSH instruction. POP removes data from the stack and places into the target registers, flags, or word memory location. Like PUSH instruction, POP is available in four forms register, register/memory, segment register, and flags.
